27:07.000 --> 27:14.000
that demarcated a very important milestone because before, the only thing you could do to manipulate biology was essentially look very natural.

27:14.000 --> 27:21.000
You could graft a plant on top of another plant. People have been doing that for tens of thousands of years.

27:21.000 --> 27:28.000
Nobody ever thought that would be either an ethical or potentially controversial. People have been breeding dogs, etc.

27:28.000 --> 27:35.000
But the moment you could actually do it molecularly and actually infringe on the domain of the most sacred molecules, DNA,

27:35.000 --> 27:39.000
then all of a sudden things escalate to tremendous proportion.

27:39.000 --> 27:48.000
I think, you know, obviously, one of the things that actually Mark said, I think, is extremely important is that we live to be a system of homeostasis

27:48.000 --> 27:54.000
and actually 90% of our machinery is to keep the cell doing exactly what it's doing regardless of perturbation.

27:54.000 --> 28:01.000
But the biggest domestic system is the actual world. If you go outside, you know, one of the biggest problems you have right now,

28:01.000 --> 28:05.000
people try to engineer algae to produce lipids at much higher rates.

28:05.000 --> 28:10.000
So you, for instance, get better biofuel production. And people have been very successful doing that.

28:10.000 --> 28:14.000
You know why we're not producing fuels? Because the moment you actually start breeding these things in normal environment,

28:14.000 --> 28:18.000
they are immediately out-competed by normal algae that don't do that.

28:18.000 --> 28:26.000
And so that's the way of the plan of getting back and basically telling you, look, yeah, you produce more fuel, but for the planet, it's not very helpful.

28:26.000 --> 28:31.000
And so these species will actually be out-competed and will eventually die. It will become not a dominant species.

28:31.000 --> 28:39.000
So I think that we have to always come to terms with, I think, today, right in New York Times that our CO2 levels are the highest in

28:39.000 --> 28:46.000
400 million years. That worries me. I think a lot more. Because that can trigger an absolute irreversible catastrophe and

28:46.000 --> 28:53.000
finance and no way to react to that. Most of the living organisms, if you think of the number of species that we have

28:53.000 --> 29:00.000
and the number of genetic experiments that are happening every day, and each one of them, just because of, you know, normal rates of mutations,

29:00.000 --> 29:03.000
almost everything that you could possibly do in the lab is actually being done out there.

29:03.000 --> 29:11.000
So when you say we're synthesizing new virus for influenza, is lethal and can transmit to man-to-man? That's being done every day out there.

29:11.000 --> 29:15.000
I have to disagree with that. I have to go back to what I said before and disagree with that.

29:15.000 --> 29:19.000
I think the current and the next stage of synthetic biology are profoundly different.

29:19.000 --> 29:25.000
It's not just ionizing radiation and individual mutations, and it's not just sampling sequences that may have been already sampled.

29:25.000 --> 29:36.000
I think it's at the point now when one can design proteins entirely from scratch that are not mutationly related to anything that's been seen on Earth before.

29:36.000 --> 29:43.000
And one can sample new sequences, both protein and DNA sequences, that are unrelated to anything that's ever been around.

29:43.000 --> 29:47.000
And I think that's a fundamentally different thing. It's not just making mutations.

29:47.000 --> 29:52.000
Michael, has anything been created like that that can be a specific example?

29:52.000 --> 30:08.000
Well, that's what my lab does. But there's also, I mean, I think in terms of protein design, there's David Baker in Seattle who's doing computational work to design proteins entirely from scratch with predetermined folds and predetermined activities

30:08.000 --> 30:12.000
that are unrelated to anything that any sequences that exist on Earth.

30:12.000 --> 30:18.000
My own work, we're making libraries of novel sequences unrelated to anything that has ever existed on Earth.

30:18.000 --> 30:23.000
And if a sequence base is larger than can it ever been sampled with a history of the universe?

30:23.000 --> 30:32.000
And someone can now make sequences that have never existed before and then challenge those sequences to provide to see whether they can provide life-sustaining functions.

30:32.000 --> 30:43.000
So one can actually go into bacterial cells, knock out parts of the genome, and then see if those parts of the genome can be replaced by sequences that never existed before.

30:43.000 --> 30:51.000
So if you do that, if you take a bacterial cell that has 4,000 genes and you replace four of them, well then it's an E. coli that's a little weird and it has four new genes.

30:51.000 --> 30:56.000
Again, these are not mutant genes. These are genes unrelated to anything that ever existed.

30:56.000 --> 31:12.000
So if you do it four out of four thousand, it's a minor thing. But when you start, I'm not going to do this, but we can imagine just around the corner that people can now replace large sections of a genome of, let's say, a bacterial cell with sequences that never existed before in the history of the Earth.

31:12.000 --> 31:20.000
And then that, I think, one has to come to grips with the fact that those are new forms of life that are not evolutionary variants of existing forms of life.

31:20.000 --> 31:26.000
They're fundamentally new, fundamentally new sequences, proteins designed from scratch, genomes designed from scratch.

31:26.000 --> 31:34.000
That, I think, is around the corner and I think that's, you know, in terms of philosophical or theological issues, that's sort of something that one wants to think about.

31:34.000 --> 31:42.000
Another thing would be chemotherapy. Often we use nucleoside anelones. We have variations of AC, G, and T that are just different enough that they killed the cells.

31:42.000 --> 31:47.000
And so you can use synthetic biology. I would even argue that chemotherapy could be viewed as a form of synthetic...

31:47.000 --> 31:56.000
And the genetic, the genetic code there. We're 20 amino acids for as long as the world's been around, but we can now engineer the genetic code to have more than 20 amino acids.

31:56.000 --> 32:10.000
What is the... I'm trying to understand the grasp of at least the fundamental semantic difference between having a protein that is completely different from another one and got to be completely different because of some very complex evolutionary path.

32:10.000 --> 32:12.000
God there, one that you would engineer from scratch.

